T1  - Institutional Trade Persistence and Long-Term Equity Returns
AU  - DASGUPTA, AMIL
AU  - PRAT, ANDREA
AU  - VERARDO, MICHELA
Y1  - 2011/04/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2010.01644.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 635
EP  - 653
VL  - 66
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2010.01644.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Recent studies show that single-quarter institutional herding positively predicts short-term returns. Motivated by the theoretical herding literature, which emphasizes endogenous persistence in decisions over time, we estimate the effect of multiquarter institutional buying and selling on stock returns. Using both regression and portfolio tests, we find that persistent institutional trading negatively predicts long-term returns: persistently sold stocks outperform persistently bought stocks at long horizons. The negative association between returns and institutional trade persistence is not subsumed by past returns or other stock characteristics, is concentrated among smaller stocks, and is stronger for stocks with higher institutional ownership.
ER  - 

